<p>In 1668, Charles II&#8217;s court was dominated by five high councillors rather than a single favorite, raising concerns of a threat to the throne&#8217;s authority.</p>
<p>It didn&#8217;t help that their names literally spelled CABAL: (left to right) the Lord Clifford of Chudleigh, the Earl of Arlington, the Duke of Buckingham, the Lord Ashley, and the Duke of Lauderdale.</p>
<p>In fact the five were fractious and mistrustful, and the group broke up within a few years. But Lord Macaulay called them &#8220;the first germ of the present system of government by a Cabinet.&#8221;</p>
